n  # normal end\n\n    # Re-invoke agent with the interrupt response (approve or deny)\n    interrupt_responses = interrupt_data\n    current_input = None\n```\n\n**Interrupt flow clarification:**\n- The `ApprovalHook` raises the Strands interrupt via `event.interrupt(\"strands-approval\", ...)` inside `BeforeToolCallEvent` before tool execution.\n- Strands pauses execution and `stream_async()` ends with `result.stop_reason == \"interrupt\"`.\n- The stream ends, and the adapter has already yielded the `TOOL_CALL` event and is waiting at `await self._approval_event.wait()`.\n- On `approve_tool(tool_id, approved=True)`: adapter builds `[{\"interruptResponse\": {\"interruptId\": interrupt_id, \"response\": \"approved\"}}]` and re-invokes `agent.stream_async(interrupt_responses)`. Strands resumes from the interrupt point, runs the tool, and continues the agent loop.\n- On `approve_tool(tool_id, approved=False)`: adapter builds the same structure with `\"response\": \"denied\"`, the `ApprovalHook.approve()` sees a non-\"y\" response and sets `event.cancel_tool = \"User denied\"`. Strands skips tool execution and continues the loop.\n- In both cases the outer `while True` loop re-enters `stream_async()` with the interrupt response payload.\n- The `interrupt_id` comes from the interrupt raised in `ApprovalHook.approve()`. The adapter stores this id (passed via the interrupt reason dict) when yielding the `TOOL_CALL` event."
